This paper is likely to belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category as it deals with nearest neighbor search and maximum inner product search, which are common tasks in information retrieval. It also involves vector quantization, which is a technique commonly used in information retrieval. 

It could also belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category as maximum inner product search is a common task in computer vision, particularly in image retrieval. 

The paper also involves machine learning techniques such as product quantization and multiscale quantization, which are commonly used in the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. 

The use of large scale datasets and detailed ablation tests suggests that this paper could also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. 

Finally, the use of multiscale quantization and vector quantization suggests that this paper could also belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category, which deals with the processing and analysis of multimedia data.
